<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Says Kinkel Comments `Adventurous Speculation' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801180194 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 17 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["tl"-signed report: "Election Programs Concentrate on </F>
Economic, Financial Issues"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The political parties represented in the 
Bundestag are increasingly focusing on economic and financial 
policy issues. Rudolf Scharping, chairman of the Social 
Democratic Party of Germany [SPD], said in Bonn on 17 January 
that the determination with which the SPD has concentrated on 
the great economic and social issues is decisive for the party's 
"successful course." This includes an economic policy forum on 
the modernization of Germany's economic base, at which the SPD 
will discuss its government program with entrepreneurs later 
this month. 
  Prior to the Federal Government's 17 January meeting on 
additional spending cuts of DM7.5 billion, Scharping doubted 
that the planned new borrowing could be limited to DM70 billion. 
Scharping said Federal Finance Minister Theo Waigel's 
(Christian Social Union -- CSU) budget "borders on a 
falsification of the balance sheet." 
  There were differences of opinion on the budget policy 
within 
the Free Democratic Party [FDP]. According to party chairman 
Klaus Kinkel, the government will not survive 1994 without a 
supplementary budget. This was rejected by Federal Economics 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt (FDP) as "adventurous speculation." At 
the ministers' meeting, Kinkel rejected additional spending cuts 
in the defense and educational sectors. He said the Bundeswehr 
was not the nation's reserve cash box. Following talks with 
scientific organizations, Kinkel stressed the importance of 
biotechnology for Germany as an investment center. The 
Christian Democratic Union presented its economic program on 17 
January. It is supposed to show ways out of the economic crisis 
over the medium term and was approved by the party's leading 
bodies at a closed meeting in Windhagen near Bonn last weekend 
[15-16 January]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

