<H3> <TI>   Solana Signs Cooperation Agreements With South Korea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701094294 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 0700 GMT 
17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701094294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Foreign Minister Javier Solana is 
continuing his Far East tour. After visiting Japan, he is now 
in South Korea, where he has signed five economic cooperation 
agreements, two extradition agreements, and a cultural relations 
agreement. Thailand and Malaysia will be his next destinations. 
In statements to ``Spain at Seven'' [this newscast], the 
minister highlighted Spain's interest in this region because of 
its trading importance: 
  [Begin Solana recording] We have made a package of 
agreements 
with a country that is of increasing importance in this region, 
that is growing greatly, and whose trade with Spain is also 
growing. In the last three years we have practically doubled 
our export rate to these countries, and to this particular 
country, to Korea, and we must maintain that pressure because 
they are, (?as I said,) countries that are of increasing 
importance in international trade. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

