<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkic Summit Postponement `Surprise Decision' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1801185694 London Kanal-6 Television in Turkish 1700 GMT 
18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1801185694 </F>
<F P=104>  London Kanal-6 Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Azerbaijan made a surprise decision to postpone the 
summit of the heads of state of six Turkic republics, scheduled 
to be held in Baku on 21 and 22 January. It was learned that 
the uneasiness felt by Russia over a Turkic summit was the 
reason for the postponement. 
  Besides, it is being claimed that Uzbekistan and 
Turkmenistan 
wanted the summit to be postponed to avoid giving the impression 
that the summit is a front against Armenia. Whereas, the 
Azerbaijani Government stated that the summit was postponed to 
allow for better preparations for it. 
  The second summit of the Turkic republics -- the first was 
held in Turkey in 1992 -- would have been held in Baku at the 
end of 1993. However, Geydar Aliyev postponed the summit until 
January. Ankara was surprised by Aliyev's decision to postpone 
it for a second time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

