<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Syria Reportedly Sends PKK Leader to Beirut </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1801193794 London Kanal-6 Television in Turkish 1700 GMT 
18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1801193794 </F>
<F P=104>  London Kanal-6 Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following Clinton's warning to Syrian leader Hafiz 
al-Asad on PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] terrorism, attention 
has now been riveted on possible measures Damascus has taken 
against the PKK and Apo [PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan]. 
  It was learned that as a first step in this context, Syria 
has forced Apo to leave Damascus and that the PKK leader is in 
the Lebanese capital, Beirut. 
  [Begin unidentified reporter recording] It is a known fact 
that Syria does not want to lose its PKK trump card against 
Turkey. However, Hafiz al-Asad, who wants to integrate with the 
West and who openly expressed this intention to Clinton, is 
expected to further hem in on Apo. According to available 
information, Syria took its first step on this issue recently 
and forced PKK leader Apo to leave for the Lebanese capital of 
Beirut. Apo currently is being kept under control in Beirut. 
  Considering Syria's influence on Lebanon, however, it 
appears 
that al-Asad will not give up its Apo and PKK trump cards, at 
least until he gets Turkey's consent for an agreement on river 
water. 
  Sending Apo off to Beirut is perceived by Ankara as an 
indication of goodwill from the Damascus government. However, 
Ankara believes Damascus has to take more positive steps. 
Ankara is now getting ready to launch a diplomatic offensive in 
Washington to further pressure Damascus on the PKK and Apo. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

