<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rome To Provide Support for Bosnian Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1101104094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2026 GMT 10 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1101104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia: Italy Ready With Logistical </F>
Support in Event of.... Air Strikes"] 
  [Text] Rome, 10 Jan (ANSA) -- Italy stands ready to provide 
logistical support in the event of an air strike on Bosnia, 
Defense Minister Fabio Fabbri said in a radio interview to be 
aired Tuesday morning [11 January] but excerpts of which were 
released here tonight. 
  With reference to the ongoing NATO summit in Brussels, 
Fabbri 
said that the Atlantic Alliance must be ready to intervene 
energetically in Bosnia if called upon to do so, however he 
noted that the final decision rests with the United Nations. 
  The defense minister voiced satisfaction with the fact that 
the Bosnian question was being debated at the summit and 
recalled that NATO has on several occasions stressed it was 
willing to intervene with air strikes to protect humanitarian 
convoys and to break the Serbian stranglehold on Sarajevo. 
  In any case, there is no contingency plan to send Italian 
soldiers to Bosnia as the United Nations rightfully insists that 
the participation of troops from neighboring nations is 
undesirable, Fabbri added. 

</TEXT>

