<F P=101> Italy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi: Relations With Russia on G-7 Agenda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1101105294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2232 GMT 10 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1101105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "NATO: Ciampi and Clinton on G-7; </F>
Andreatta on CSCE"] 
  [Text] Rome, 10 Jan (ANSA) -- The coming Naples summit of 
the Group of Seven [G-7] of the world's leading industrial 
nations must be an occasion to demonstrate with concrete facts 
the spirit with which the West wants to carry forward its 
relations with Russia, according to Italian Premier Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi who took up the theme again with United States 
President Bill Clinton this evening during a brief encounter on 
the sidelines of the NATO summit underway here. 
  According to Ciampi, the dialogue with Russia must be 
constructive. This dialogue must see the West committed to 
spurring Moscow to carry on with its reforms, while at the same 
time aiding Russia to overcome this difficult and lengthy 
transition period, Ciampi said. 
  During his speech to the summit, Ciampi said that giving 
greater political emphasis to the coming G-7 summit meant making 
a valid contribution to a dialogue for even greater 
rapprochement between Russia and the West. 
  Italian Foreign Minister Beniamino Andreatta Monday [10 
January] also stressed the need for a tie-in between NATO and 
the Conference for Security and Cooperation in Europe, stating 
that CSCE peacekeeping missions, above all in Asia and in the 
republics of the former Soviet Union, cannot help but draw on 
Russian national interest which must, however, be 
internationalized, not an instrument of an imperialistic policy. 
  While on the subject of peace-keeping, Andreatta said that 
the experience in Somalia and Bosnia has suggested that the use 
of military units is not always the most suitable instrument for 
operations having a large humanitarian content. There is a need 
to find crowd control measures which are not lethal in nature, 
he said. 
  Italy has also called for greater and more analytical ground 
observations so as to better identify those responsible for 
truce-breaking. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

