<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Summit Ends; No Agreement on Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1101125794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 0956 GMT 11 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1101125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "NATO: Summit Ends With No Movement </F>
on Bosnia"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 11 January (ANSA) -- The NATO summit ended 
here today without reaching agreement on new wording for a 
threatened air strike on Serb forces that might achieve the 
re-opening of the airport at Tuzla or free access for United 
Nations forces to the Muslim enclave at Srebrenica, diplomatic 
sources said. 
  The summit's final communique restricted itself to inviting 
the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] command in Bosnia to 
"urgently draw up plans to ensure the rotation of the UN forces 
at Srebrenica and to examine how to reopen the airport at 
Tuzla," without referring to military action that NATO might 
undertake to achieve these goals. 
  The document reiterated last August's reference to air 
strikes that may be undertaken by NATO -- at the request of UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali -- to prevent the 
"strangulation" of the Bosnian capital Sarajevo and the other 
Muslim safe areas in the former Yugoslav republic. 
  Reports from Sarajevo said Serb bombardments had ceased this 
morning after the newly raised NATO threat of air strikes in 
Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-58694 </DOCNO>
