<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Strategic Alliance' With Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101155194 Hamburg DPA in German 1451 GMT 11 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1101155194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mainz (DPA) -- NATO Secretary General Manfred 
Woerner has said that the alliance is aiming for a "strategic 
alliance" with Russia. In an interview with ZDF today, Woerner 
said "what we want is a greater Europe, if you will, a lasting 
Euro-Atlantic community with the Russians so that they do not 
have the feeling of being excluded or even encircled." 
  Woerner defended the concept of Partnership for Peace with 
the countries of Central and East Europe that was approved at 
the NATO summit in Brussels, and pointed out that consultations 
were envisaged in the event of a crisis. Even though there were 
no security guarantees for these countries as yet, this did not 
mean "that we will stand idly by if they are attacked." 
  As for NATO's attitude to the Bosnia conflict, Woerner said, 
with regard to possible air strikes in Bosnia, the alliance 
depended on the approval of the United Nations. The opinion of 
UN troops on the ground also had to be heard. However, he had 
the impression that there was "much greater determination" in 
the alliance: "Things cannot stay the way they are." 

</TEXT>

