<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Commander Opposes Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501101094 Hamburg DPA in German 0316 GMT 15 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1501101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DPA) -- Francis Briquemont, commander in 
chief of the UN troops stationed in the war zone [in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina], has strongly criticized the West's position 
toward the war in Bosnia. In an interview with the news 
magazine DER SPIEGEL, the Belgian general said he is tired of 
listening to NATO's threats of air strikes on Serb positions. 
Air strikes cannot solve the problems of the surrounded and 
besieged towns and cities like Sarajevo. Permanent threats will 
not make the warring parties more willing to make peace. The 
West lacks a clear strategy. Too many opinions are being 
expressed, too many resolutions passed, but not enough funds are 
being made available to implement the political objectives. 
  The general, who will give up the supreme command of the UN 
troops in former Yugoslavia earlier than scheduled, said the 
Blue Helmets will therefore "soon be unable to continue to 
provide humanitarian aid." Unless a peace plan is agreed 
quickly, the Blue Helmet mission as a whole will need to be 
questioned. Briquemont said literally: "It is an illusion to 
believe that the UN troops can continue to provide humanitarian 
aid indefinitely when shots continue to be fired at the same 
time." 
  The article was prereleased in an edited version. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

