<H3> <TI>   Kohl Rejects `Numbers Games' on Bundeswehr Size </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101090294 Hamburg DPA in German 0300 GMT 11 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1101090294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Osnabrueck (DPA) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl 
rejected a "rash and half-baked numbers games" about the size of 
the Bundeswehr. Pointing to the situation in former Yugoslavia 
in an interview with the NEUE OSNABRUECKER ZEITUNG (Tuesday [11 
January] edition), Kohl said peace and freedom could still not 
be had free of charge. For him, it is still decisive "that our 
armed forces are capable of meeting our alliance obligations, 
prepared for action, and equipped to modern standards, and that 
we retain conscription," Kohl said. 
  Kohl warned against setbacks to the process of reform in the 
states of the former Warsaw Pact, above all in Russia. This 
would have "unforeseeable consequences." So far, Germany has 
provided the lion's share of aid --amounting to 80 billion 
German marks -- to Russia and the states of the former Soviet 
Union (The interview was prereleased to DPA in edited form). 

</TEXT>

