<H3> <TI>   Government, Iranian Officials Meet in Bonn </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bonn Expects Pardon for Engineer </H4>
<F P=102> LD1101224594 Hamburg DPA in German 1506 GMT 11 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1101224594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Bonn (DPA) -- Mohamad Javad Larijani, former 
Iranian deputy foreign minister, will make efforts to bring 
about the release of German engineer Helmut Szimkus, who has 
been sentenced to death in Iran. 
  Larijani said this in talks with representatives of the 
German Government and parliament in Bonn. He is heading a small 
delegation of parliamentarians on a two-day visit to Bonn. 
Larijani is regarded as a close confidant of Iranian President 
'Ali Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani. In their talks with him, 
Bundestag President Rita Suessmuth and Foreign Ministry State 
Secretary Dieter Kastrup directly raised the issue of the 
existing plea for pardon and asked for support. 
  According to information available to DPA, the German 
Government now assumes that Szimkus, who is accused of spying 
for Iraq, will be pardoned in the spring. "Despite the 
difficulties, we are quite certain of this," a high-ranking 
government official told DPA. Under no circumstances is the 
Szimkus case "a matter for negotiation" in connection with the 
Mykonos trial in Berlin. [passage omitted] 
  The three members of the Iranian parliamentary delegation 
did 
not raise the issue of the Mykonos trial in their talks, which 
included a meeting late this afternoon with Bernd Schmidtbauer, 
state minister at the chancellor's office. This was confirmed 
by Christoph Matschke, chairman of the German-Iranian group of 
parliamentarians, which invited Larijani and his delegation to 
Germany. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

