<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Grants To East To Decrease in 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301170994 Hamburg DPA in German 1055 GMT 13 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1301170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- After three years of rising 
government grants and subsidies from western to eastern Germany, 
1994 will for the first time show a reduction in comparison with 
the previous year. In response to a query from DDP/ADN, the 
Finance Ministry revealed in Bonn on Thursday [13 January] that 
a total of 138 billion German marks [DM] was transferred to 
eastern Germany last year. In 1994, this sum will fall by DM5 
billion to DM133 billion net (DM175 billion gross). [passage 
omitted] 
  In 1991, DM107 billion net was made available for eastern 
Germany. In 1992, this sum rose to DM115 billion and was 
increased again last year by DM23 billion, according to official 
figures. That was the highest level of payments since German 
unification. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

