<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundeswehr Expects `Drastic' Budget Cut </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501201494 Hamburg DPA in German 1817 GMT 15 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1501201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DPA) -- According to a report in WELT AM 
SONNTAG, the Bundeswehr must expect further drastic cuts 
totaling at least 1 to 1.2 billion German marks [DM] in the 
current fiscal year. The latest figure, which Bundeswehr 
leaders did not expect to be so high, was part of the savings 
package the government and coalition want to use to bridge a 
budget deficit of DM5 billion. 
  Defense Minister Volker Ruehe (CDU) and other ministers 
affected by the cuts will meet Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl on 
17 January. The Bundestag group leadership is to hold 
discussions on 18 January, and on 19 January the budget 
committee is to discuss the necessary cuts, the paper adds. 
  The Defense Ministry leadership and defense experts in the 
government coalition were planning to absorb most of the latest 
cuts within the existing structures and with a planned 
Bundeswehr size of 370,000 men. The Defense Ministry hoped that 
these would be the last cuts and that the Bundeswehr would have 
a budget of DM47.5 billion at its disposal from 1995, as agreed 
between the chancellor and the finance and defense ministers. 
  (An edited version of the article was prereleased to DPA) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

