<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Butrus-Ghali Visits Netherlands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2001152194 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 20 Jan 94 p 
6 </F>

<F P=103> BR2001152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Butrus-Ghali Praises Netherlands </F>
Role--`Important Military Contributions to UN Peace Operations'"] 
  [Text] UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali has given 
the Netherlands lavish praise for the important military 
contribution it is making to UN peace operations. Butrus-Ghali 
was speaking to members of Parliament and the Senate and later 
addressed a packed Great Church in The Hague. 
  The offer to send a reinforced battalion in addition to the 
1,840 Netherlands soldiers who are already deployed in the 
former Yugoslavia was "highly valued" by the United Nations, 
Butrus-Ghali said. 
  Dutch support to mine clearance operations in 
Mozambique--the 
Netherlands is to send some 10 mine clearance experts--was also 
especially welcome. 
  The secretary general regretfully noted that some countries 
were starting to show "symptoms of fatigue" where contributions 
to UN peace operations were concerned. "I am not certain 
whether I will obtain enough troops for peace operations," he 
said. "Nor am I certain of financial contributions. Some 
countries say that the costs and risks are too high." 
  In a confidential speech to members of Parliament and the 
Senate, Butrus-Ghali said he could not impose peace in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina if the warring parties continued to refuse to 
end the hostilities. The order to launch air attacks on Bosnian 
Serb positions was a matter for the UN member states themselves. 
<H5>  Borrow </H5>
  Butrus-Ghali, who is on a three-day visit to the 
Netherlands, 
added that he could only "borrow" military resources from the UN 
member states. The decision to launch air attacks was not his 
first responsibility, he said. NATO has spoken in favor of air 
attacks, but so far Butrus-Ghali has received no request to 
carry them out. 
  Prince Willem-Alexander, virtually the entire cabinet, MP's, 
the military top brass, and many prominent Dutch persons 
attended the secretary general's speech in the Great Church. 
Butrus-Ghali is a former international law professor in Egypt, 
his country of birth. He called for breathing new life into 
international law so that it would be possible to react 
appropriately to the great challenges of the post-Cold War 
period. He referred to the great role the Netherlands has long 
played in this respect. It was not for nothing that The Hague 
houses the UN International Court of Justice, the Permanent 
Court of Arbitration, and the International War Crimes Tribunal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

