<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   South Africa Invited To Rejoin Commonwealth </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901200394 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1827 GMT 19 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901200394 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Finlay Marshall, PRESS ASSOCIATION] </F>
  [Text] South Africa was tonight invited to rejoin the 
Commonwealth after a 33-year absence. The offer came from the 
Secretary General of the Commonwealth Secretariat, Chief Emeka 
Anyaoku, when he spoke at London's South Africa Club. 
  He said: "The Commonwealth's 50 member countries drawn from 
all the continents and regions of the world will provide the new 
South Africa with a ready gateway to the wider world." 
  Chief Anyaoku said that central to the resolution of South 
Africa's accumulated problems will be its ability to reintegrate 
fully into the world community of nations. He invited South 
Africa to heal the "family rift" now that it was becoming a 
non-racial democracy. 
  South Africa will hold its first democratic elections on 
April 27 with all races able to vote after its Parliament 
approved an interim constitution leading to black majority rule. 
  Chief Anyaoku said: "By normalising its relations with the 
Commonwealth, South Africa will at a stroke be consolidating its 
relations with 50 other countries with influence and a network 
of relations in their respective regions." 
  He added: "A post apartheid South Africa, reconciled and at 
peace with itself and its neighbours, will, as far as the 
Commonwealth is concerned, be sufficient reward in itself. It 
will be a triumph for the most cherished of all Commonwealth 
principles, namely, the equality of all human beings 
irrespective of colour, religious belief, culture or any other 
adventitious criteria," he said. 

</TEXT>

