<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economics Minister: Welfare Structures Hampering Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001142494 Hamburg DPA in German 1241 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DPA) -- Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt 
complained of "fossilized welfare state structures" today. He 
said before the German World Economic Association today in 
Berlin that the "ossification of institutions and behavior 
patterns in our society" were delaying the necessary structural 
adjustments and jeopardizing the competitiveness of German 
industry. 
  The far-reaching changes in the global economy were a 
challenge to the Western world. The technological advantage of 
the old industrial countries was shrinking. The European and 
German superiority in the quality of work could no longer be 
taken for granted. 
  In Germany, said Rexrodt, the economy in the new eastern 
states was noticeably catching up with that in the West, 
"despite all prophecies of doom". It was particularly 
gratifying to note that the processing industry, which had so 
far "lagged behind", was now catching up. This could be seen 
from the increase in incoming contracts and strong production 
growth of just under eight percent in 1993. 

</TEXT>

