<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Visits, Meets Officials </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001203494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2000 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Batyrev] </F>
  [Text] Paris January 20 TASS -- Our present visit to France 
is highly unusual because Georgia is now very much interested in 
establishing new relationships with its partners, and we attach 
great importance to this trip, Georgian leader Eduard 
Shevardnadze told ITAR-TASS upon arriving in France for a 
two-day visit. 
  Georgia became an independent state only recently and quite 
naturally we seek to build our new equitable relations with 
other sovereign states by developing a solid legal framework for 
them, the Georgian leader said about the aim of his visit to 
France. 
  During his two-day visit Shevardnadze will be received by 
French President Francois Mitterrand and sign with him a treaty 
of accord, friendship and cooperation between the two countries, 
as well as sign the Paris Charter for a New Europe. 
  Journalists who met Shevardnadze in Paris pestered him with 
questions about prospects for relations between Georgia and 
Russia. "Directly upon my return home, I will begin preparations 
for a very important event -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin's 
visit to Tbilisi," Shevardnadze said. Yeltsin's trip to Georgia 
is scheduled for the beginning of February. 
  "We are bound with Russia by many ties, and the Russian 
president's visit to Georgia is a major event in many years of 
our life," Georgian leader said. Yeltsin's visit to Tbilisi is 
designed to define relations of friendship and cooperation 
between the two sovereign states. 
  "Georgia is now entering a period of stability after the 
threat on unleashing a large-scale civil war has been 
eliminated", Shevardnadze said. "After we settle the conflict 
with, the man task for us is to ensure the country's normal 
economic development," he said. One of the principal conditions 
needed for progress in this field is Russia's continuous 
democratic evolution. If this evolution is disrupted, most 
unfavourable developments can ensue, Shevardnadze said. 
  Also on Thursday [20 January], Shevardnadze met the leaders 
of two international organisations based in Paris - Federico 
Mayor, Director-general of the United Nations 
Educational,Scientific and Cultural Organisation (UNESCO) and 
Jean Claude Payem, director general of the Organisation for 
Economic Cooperation and Development to discuss prospects for 
the development of relations between Georgia and UNESCO, Georgia 
and OECD. Business cooperation between Georgia and France was 
discussed in headquarters of the National Council of French 
Entrepreneurs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-58762 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu014_i_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

