<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mitterrand, Norway's Brundtland Discuss EC Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101073694 Paris AFP in English 2102 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101073694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 20 (AFP) -- Norwegian Prime Minister Gro 
Harlem Brundtland discussed Norway's bid to join the European 
Community during a meeting with French President Francois 
Mitterrand on Thursday [20 January]. 
  In a half-hour meeting with Mitterrand, Brundtland stressed 
the need to find solutions to problems brought up in 
negotiations over Norway's possible membership in the EC. 
  Addressing European Parliament deputies in Strasbourg 
earlier 
Thursday, Brundtland said negotiations over the expansion of the 
EC could be concluded by March 1. 
  "This is an ambitious target, but if the political will is 
there, it is feasible," she said. 
  The main obstacles to Norway's EC membership remain 
agriculture and fishing, the prime minister said. 
  As for agriculture, Norway is seeking "some special 
arrangements adapted to our climate and topographic situation," 
Brundtland said. 
  Oslo is also requesting "creative reflection" to solve the 
problem of the management of northern Norwegian fishing areas, 
she added. 
  "So far we have achieved encouraging results related to 
energy and also regarding environmental standards. We have also 
met a constructive approach to regional policy," she said. 
  The EC has fixed February 28 as the deadline for concluding 
negotiations on EC membership with Norway, Austria, Finland and 
Sweden, so that these countries may join the community in early 
1995. 
  Speaking in Strasbourg Wednesday, Greek European Affairs 
Minister Theodoros Pangalos, whose country currently holds the 
rotating EC presidency, did not rule out that this deadline 
could be extended. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

