<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hurd Meets Cetin; Begins Official Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1901174694 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1901174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Douglas Hurd, British secretary 
of state for foreign and Commonwealth affairs, visited Foreign 
Minister Hikmet Cetin in Ankara today. Following the 
tete-a-tete meeting between the two ministers, official talks 
began between the Turkish and British delegations. 
  In a statement before the talks, Hurd expressed pleasure 
over 
meeting with Cetin, with whom he is in direct contact or speaks 
to on the telephone almost once a month. Pointing out that 
bilateral relations, terrorism, human rights, and the recent 
developments in Iraq and Bosnia-Herzegovina were discussed with 
Cetin, Hurd noted that a tripartite meeting will be held 
tomorrow in which German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel will 
participate as well. 
  Cetin declared in turn that relations between Turkey and 
Britain are extremely positive, and there are no problems 
between the two countries. During the talks with the visiting 
minister, agreement was reached to further develop bilateral 
relations, Cetin remarked. He noted that Turkey has always 
enjoyed British support in its relations with Europe, expressing 
the belief that this support will continue in the future as well. 
  Hurd was then received by Prime Minister Tansu Ciller. Cetin 
and the two countries' ambassadors to London and Ankara 
respectively also attended the meeting. 
  The foreign ministers of Turkey, Britain, and Germany will 
hold their tripartite consultative meeting in Ankara tomorrow. 
Kinkel will arrive in Ankara tonight to attend the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

