<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demirel Comments on Potential Russian Military Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1901200194 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1901200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Excerpt] Addressing a lesson on international relations at 
the Ground War School during a tour of the school today, 
President Suleyman Demirel noted that the civilized world today, 
at least in theory, rejects using force to solve problems. 
Despite this, Demirel remarked, there are incidents in 
Yugoslavia and the Caucasus. Extreme nationalism, racism, 
sectarianism, and xenophobia lie at the base of this problem, 
the president explained. 
  Pointing out that there are 3,000 different languages and 
179 
countries in the world today, Demirel continued: 
  [Begin Demirel recording] If every different ethnic group 
and sect claims a different flag and demands independence, then 
3,000 states must be established. Geography is also not 
conducive to this. People live intermingled with one another. 
People are happy when they live without making an issue of 
their origins and their beliefs, and when they show tolerance 
for each other and accept one another. [end recording] 
  Demirel recounted that the Soviet Union, which covered 22 
million square km, collapsed, but Russia today includes 70 
percent of this territory and its population. Noting that the 
Red Army is still standing and that there are close to 20,000 
nuclear warheads in Russia, Demirel said intensive diplomatic 
contacts are under way throughout the whole world in order to 
prevent the reemergence of a military threat and a return to the 
old days. 
  Demirel concluded by saying Turkey has an important place, 
name, and stature in international relations as a result of its 
60 million population and its sensitive geographical location. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

