<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Calls For Major Review of Bosnian Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2001134694 Paris AFP in English 1343 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2001134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 20 (AFP) -- French Foreign Minister 
Alain Juppe on Thursday [20 January] called for a major review 
of Bosnian policy and said he planned to quickly broach the 
issue with U.S., Russia and European partners, as disgust built 
over the latest failure of Bosnian talks. 
  Juppe said he was "offering in the coming hours and days to 
make new contact with our American, Russian and European 
partners to proceed with this overhaul." 
  "We can no longer watch on the one hand the different 
parties 
negotiate in Geneva, and on the ground watch an escalation of 
the conflict," said Juppe in a statement for the French 
Assembly's foreign affairs committee. 
  He spoke as the European parliament in Strasbourg called for 
the replacement of David Owen as European Community negotiator 
in the Bosnian negotiations in a resolution that criticized the 
strategy of EC and United Nations negotiators "who have achieved 
no results and who persist in wanting to divide 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, though a member of the United Nations, along 
ethnic lines." 
  Hans van den Broek, the European commissioner for external 
relations, meanwhile, suggested Thursday in Stasbourg that the 
EC should perhaps consider suspending its mediation efforts 
"until the three parties (in Bosnia) are ready to accept a 
durable solution." But he said it was "unfair" to blame Owen, 
since he was acting on a mandate from the EC. 
  Two days of talks on Bosnia in Geneva collapsed Wednesday 
with the Bosnian Moslems, Croats and Serbs still deadlocked, as 
international mediators held out scant hope for progress when 
talks reconvene in three weeks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

