<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Push for Full Sanctions Against Haiti </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401220994 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
2130 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2401220994 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Canada has promised to push for full sanctions 
against Haiti, unless the military allows the return of exiled 
president, Jean-Bertrand Aristide. Foreign Affairs Minister 
Andre Ouellet made the pledge during a meeting with Mr. 
Aristide, who is on a six-day visit to Canada. 
  Current sanctions imposed by the United Nations prevent oil 
and weapons from reaching the Caribbean island, but Ottawa wants 
the ban made complete in order to prevent Haiti from receiving 
anything except aid from nongovernmental organizations. 
  Mr. Ouellet said Canada and the other three so-called 
friends 
of Haiti -- the United States, Venezuela, and France -- will 
soon put a motion before the UN Security Council, calling for 
the tougher sanctions. All four nations promised to push for a 
total embargo against Haiti if the military refused to 
relinquish power by 15 January. Mr. Aristide won Haiti's first 
democratic elections over two years ago, but was later deposed 
in a bloody coup. 

</TEXT>

