<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Slavomacedonia' Rejected as Compromise Name </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2201154894 Athens ATHENS NEWS in English 22 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC2201154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ATHENS NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A prominent member of ruling party PASOK 
[Panhellenic Socialist Movement] has suggested "Slavomacedonia" 
is an acceptable compromise in the dispute over the name of the 
former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia, ahead of Monday's [24 
January] crucial parliamentary debate on the Skopje issue. His 
suggestion received support from ex-New Democracy minister 
Alexandros Papadhogonas but was dismissed by the government 
spokesman. 
  Pandelis Oikonomou, a member of the PASOK Central Committee, 
has been known to take up unpopular policy options which the 
party leadership sometimes later embrace, as in the case of his 
preelection stand in favor of taxing "repos." But his 
"Slavomacedonia" suggestion comes at a time when Prime Minister 
Andreas Papandreou is eager to show his government is united on 
the issue, especially after recent divergent opinions from 
European Affairs Minister Theodhoros Pangalos. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos, echoing the 
Interior Minister Akis Tsokhatzopoulos, insisted Mr. Oikonomou 
was only expressing "his personal views which have nothing to do 
with government policy." 

</TEXT>

