<H3> <TI>   Peres, 'Arafat End Self-Rule Negotiations in Oslo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2201194594 Paris AFP in English 1923 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2201194594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Oslo, Jan 22 (AFP) -- Israeli Foreign Minister 
Shimon Peres and PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat concluded talks in 
Oslo Saturday night [22 January] aimed at jumpstarting the 
stalled Palestinian self-rule negotiations. 
  The two leaders left agreeing to meet in Davos, Switzerland 
next Saturday, Foreign Ministry officials said. 
  'Arafat and Peres said they had made progress in the 
discussions, but did not go into any details. 
  Acting Foreign Minister Bjoern Tore Godal was pleased with 
the talks. 
  "I'm more optimistic now than I was a few days ago," Godal 
said. 
  "'Arafat and Peres have a deep personal commitment" to the 
discussions, he added. 
  'Arafat and the Palestinian delegation left the meeting for 
the airport, due to fly to Saudi Arabia, while Peres was due to 
leave Sunday morning. 

