<H3> <TI>   Addresses Session, Explains Greek Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1901141994 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1300 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1901141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The European Parliament's [EP] plenary session 
accepted the Greek presidency's program without substantive 
criticism. Reservations were expressed only regarding the white 
paper's implementation. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified correspondent] Theodhoros 
Pangalos, the Greek alternate foreign minister and president of 
the Council of Ministers, presented the Greek presidency's 
program to the European Parliament's plenary session. Pangalos 
particularly stressed what could be expected from a presidency 
in an international environment that is very unstable, 
experiencing serious crises, and suffering clashes. In his 
address, Pangalos stressed that the Greek Government attaches 
particular importance to implementing the white paper on 
employment and development. He said he hopes this will not be 
hindered by financial obstacles. 
  Discussing the European Union's [EU] expansion with four new 
members from the North, Pangalos referred specifically to 
Cyprus' application. 
  Referring to EU initiatives on common foreign policy, 
Pangalos mentioned the Greek presidency's sensitivity toward 
promoting peace and security in the Balkans and working toward 
resolving the tension in the former Yugoslavia. This position 
was accepted, the Greek presidency indirectly clarifying that it 
will not exploit the presidency to promote a national policy on 
the Balkans. This is why Pangalos carefully avoided mentioning 
Skopje or Turkey's policy toward Greece, something that was 
criticized by KKE [Greek Communist Party] Eurodeputy 
Efraimidhis. Replying to Efraimidhis, Pangalos said he was 
speaking for Greece as the EU president, not as a Greek 
nationalist who could satisfy his own wishes. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

