<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inflation in EC Rises to 3.3 Percent in December </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101145794 Paris AFP in English 1449 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Luxembourg, Jan 21 (AFP) -- The 12-monthly rate of 
inflation in the European Community (EC) rose in December to 3.3 
percent representing an increase of 0.1 percent from the rate in 
November, the EC Eurostat institute reported on Friday [21 
January]. 
  But the institute said that the figure of 3.3 percent was 
the 
lowest for a calendar year since 1987, when it had been 3.4 
percent. 
  Half of the EC countries met the inflation criteria laid 
down 
in the Maastricht Treaty on European Union for meeting targets 
for economic convergence. 
  These countries were Denmark, Ireland, the Netherlands, 
Britain, France and Belgium. Under the treaty, the annual rate 
of inflation must not exceed the average of the three lowest 
rates by more than 1.5 percentage points. 
  But Sweden and Austria, which are negotiating to join the 
Community, did not meet the criteria. Inflation in Sweden was 
4.8 percent and in Austria it was 3.5 percent. 
  Two other candidates for membership are Finland, with 
inflation of 1.5 percent, and Norway with 1.8 percent. 
  The inflation rates for the 12 months to December were: 
Belgium 2.7 percent (from 2.4 percent in December 1992), 
Britain 1.9 percent (2.6 percent), Denmark 1.5 percent (1.5 
percent), France 2.1 percent on a provisional basis (1.9 
percent), western Germany 3.7 percent (3.7 percent), Greece 12.1 
percent (14.3 percent), Ireland 1.5 percent (2.5 percent), Italy 
4.4 percent (4.6 percent), Luxembourg 3.6 percent (2.9 
percent), the Netherlands 1.7 percent (2.9 percent), Portugal 
6.4 percent (8.5 percent), and Spain 4.9 percent (5.3 percent). 

</TEXT>

