<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vranitzky Rejects Busek's Idea of Regular Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1901171994 Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN in German 19 
Jan 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU1901171994 </F>
<F P=104>  Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "pur": "Vranitzky Strictly Against Regular </F>
Army"] 
  [Excerpt] Vienna -- On 18 January Chancellor Franz 
Vranitzky sharply rejected the idea of a regular army, which was 
suggested by Austrian People's Party [OeVP] Chairman Erhard 
Busek. The chief of the Social Democratic Party of Austria 
[SPOe] said that all objective facts speak against such a form 
of national defense; moreover, Busek's move had come "absolutely 
at the wrong time." The restructuring of the Army, which was 
agreed upon in 1992, would only be implemented in two years and, 
therefore, one could not think about introducing something new 
now. In addition, a regular army would be much too expensive 
and had not proven successful in other countries. Defense 
Minister Werner Fasslabend (OeVP) said it should not be 
forbidden to discuss the idea of a regular army. However, in 
view of the current threat, the strength of the militia army 
could not be reduced in the next few years. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

