<H3> <TI>   Dehaene Says Government To Remain </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2201205294 Paris AFP in English 2022 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2201205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 21 (AFP) -- The centre-right coalition 
government in Belgium is to remain in power despite the 
resignation of Deputy Prime Minister Guy Coeme after he became 
embroiled in a bribery scandal, Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene 
said Saturday [22 January]. 
  After meeting the leaders of the four coalition partners, 
Dehaene said in a statement that they "wish the government to 
continue its work." 
  Two other leading socialist officials of Belgium's 
French-speaking regional government resigned Friday, a few hours 
after Coeme. 
  Guy Spitaels, former Francophone Socialist Party president 
and president of the French-speaking regional government, and 
Guy Mathot, another member of that government, announced their 
decision to the press just two hours after the Royal Palace 
announced Coeme's resignation. 
  The three leaders had been accused of taking bribes and 
channelling funds to the Socialist Party in connection with the 
1988 purchase of 46 Italian Agusta helicopters for the Belgian 
Army. 
  Coeme, 48, was defence minister at the time of the 225 
million dollar purchase. 
  A judicial investigation was launched after the 
assassination 
of former Socialist Party President Andre Cools on July 18, 1991. 
  In an article entitled "Is a fuse necessary?" the 
influential 
newspaper LA LIBRE BELGIQUE wrote Friday that the affair had 
caused dismay in the centre-left coalition of socialists and 
christian-socialists which backs Dehaene's federal government. 

</TEXT>

