<H3> <TI>   Dehaene Reshuffles Cabinet Amid `Kickback Scandal' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2301135194 Paris AFP in English 1221 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2301135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 22 (AFP) -- Belgian Prime Minister 
Jean-Luc Dehaene reshuffled his cabinet Sunday [23 January] 
following the resignation of the deputy prime minister amid a 
lingering kickback scandal. 
  Dehaene had said Saturday that his centre-left coalition 
would remain in office despite the departure of his deputy Guy 
Coeme, who stepped down after being implicated in a scandal over 
a 1988 government helicopter contract. 
  A statement from Belgium's King Albert II said Elio Di Rupo, 
culture minister of the country's French community, was named to 
replace Coeme as deputy prime minister, minister of 
communications and public enterprises. 
  Magda De Galan, former minister of social integration, 
health 
and environment, was named minister of social affairs. 
  Jacques Santkin, a member of parliament, was named minister 
of social integration, health and environment. 
  Jean-Maurice Dehousse will be in charge of infrastructure 
while conserving his post as minister of science policy, the 
statement said. 

</TEXT>

