<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, Opposition Debate Economy in Bundestag </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001132194 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1150 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn [DDP/ADN] -- The positions of the government 
coalition and opposition became further entrenched in the 
Bundestag debate on the government's financial and economic 
policy today. Finance Minister Theo Waigel and Economics 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt defended the government's action 
program to increase growth and employment, but the SPD [Social 
Democratic Party] accused the coalition of wanting to break the 
social consensus within the country. 
  Waigel stressed that the policy of consolidation was to be 
continued "without restrictions." The consolidation of public 
budgets would promote economic growth and create new investment 
opportunities for industry. The action program was a 
"consistent" continuation of the privatization policy and the 
instruments for controlling the labor market were being 
extended. In order to encourage innovation, small- and 
medium-size businesses would receive particular support. 
  Rexrodt stressed there were "clear indications" that the 
economic downturn in Germany had been overcome. Export 
prospects had improved. Optimism was justified, at least with 
regard to the economy. However, this did not apply to the 
development of the labor market. Therefore, the action program 
focused on the creation of additional jobs. 
  Ingrid Matthaeus-Maier, the deputy chairperson of the SPD 
parliamentary group, said the government was facing an economic 
and financial "pile of rubble." For months, the government had 
turned a blind eye to the rise in unemployment; now political 
action was supposed to cover up the inability to act. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

