<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Troops Reportedly Missing Ammunition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2201163994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1523 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2201163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- According to information from 
the BERLINER MORGENPOST, the units of the Western Group of 
Russian Armed Forces still stationed in Germany are missing over 
80,000 tonnes of ammunition. Major General Hartmut Foertsch, 
the federal government's authorized representative for the 
withdrawal of the Western Group, told the paper (Sunday [23 
January] edition) that on 1 January 1991, a total 677,000 tonnes 
of ammunition had been stored in Germany. Of this amount, 
580,390 tonnes had been dispatched to Russia between 1991 and 
1993. The Western Group had reported stocks of only 15,560 
tonnes of ammunition on 1 January 1994. There was uncertainty 
about the whereabouts of the missing 81,050 tonnes. 
  The general criticized the fact that the Russian side is "at 
present refusing to enter into discussion" with the German 
liaison command he heads. 

</TEXT>

