<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Finances More Housing for Returning CIS Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2201182894 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
17 Jan 94 p 17 </F>

<F P=103> AU2201182894 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "Jl": "Bonn To Finance 45,000 Apartments for </F>
CIS Soldiers by the End of 1994"] 
  [Excerpt] Frankfurt, 20 January -- Russia, Belarus, and 
Ukraine can count on significantly more apartments for their 
troops returning from the former GDR than were originally 
expected under the program financed by the Federal Government, 
according to Konrad Hinrichs, chairman of the Foreign 
Construction Commission of the Main Association of the German 
Construction Industry. Instead of the approximately 36,000 
housing units that were the subject of an agreement, it is now 
expected that approximately 45,000 units will be built at 40 
different locations. They will be handed over at the end of 
1994. 
  The Federal Government had originally made 7.8 billion 
German 
marks [DM] available for apartments, technical and social 
infrastructure, certain production facilities, and housing 
construction combines. Last year, a further DM550 million was 
added to the housing program. According to figures provided by 
Hinrichs, contracts for over 40,000 housing units at 37 
different locations have been signed. A further four or five 
locations where 5,000 housing units are to be built are still at 
the planning stage. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

