<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mitterrand Assures Shevardnadze of `Solidarity' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101171794 Paris AFP in English 1651 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 21 (AFP) -- Georgian President Eduard 
Shevardnadze and French counterpart Francois Mitterrand on 
Friday [21 January] signed a friendship treaty at the close of a 
two-day official visit by the Georgian leader. 
  Shevardnadze also initialled the Paris charter of the 
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) which 
sanctioned the end of the Cold War. 
  Shevardnadze already signed the charter in 1990 when he was 
foreign minister of the former Soviet Union. 
  Mitterrand, referring to Georgia's economic difficulties and 
the Abkhazia secession, said Tbilisi "can count on the 
solidarity of its friends." 
  In a meeting on Thursday with French business leaders, 
Shevardnadze said France could make a great contribution to 
exploiting his country's assets and pulling it out of a 
catastrophic recession. 

</TEXT>

