<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mitterrand Views Security Guarantees for East Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2201203794 Sofia KONTINENT in Bulgarian 17 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU2201203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia KONTINENT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with President Francois Mitterrand by Svetoslav </F>
Terziev; place and date not given: "Bulgaria Advanced in 
Transition Toward Democracy"] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Terzivev] Who could 
guarantee Bulgaria's security after the disappearance of the 
communist military system? Could it remain a neutral state or 
should it join the Western structures, such as NATO and the 
Western European Union [WEU]? 
  [Mitterrand] I fully understand Bulgaria's concern regarding 
the situation we call the "security vacuum" in Central and East 
Europe. There are several ways to cope with this situation. 
The sense of insecurity, which is based on military 
considerations, springs from various other forms of instability 
that are related to the country's economic, social, and even 
ethnic situation. Therefore, France has proposed initiatives of 
preventive diplomacy that aim to prevent or decrease tension. 
This is the essence of the French idea on the pact of 
stability, which was adopted by the European Union. The other 
possibilities lie in strengthening bilateral cooperation, which 
we subscribe to. The third possibility is in working to bring 
the countries of Central and East Europe closer together, on the 
one hand, and the European security organizations and 
associations, on the other. In this context, France advocates 
opening up those structures to the aforementioned countries. 
France proposed a formula for the association within the WEU of 
the countries that have already been associated or are in the 
process of associating with the European Union. 
  In addition, it is well known that the last NATO summit 
adopted the Partnership for Peace initiative. As I said in 
Brussels, this concept allows us to respond to the concern of 
states that want to associate with NATO and also avoid Russia's 
negative reaction -- which a new division of Europe would have 
caused, something that would have been detrimental to European 
security. For me, Partnership for Peace means that no threat 
could be directed against the sovereignty and territorial 
integrity of any partner state without affecting the other 
partner states. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

