<H3> <TI>   Andre Rossinot Elected Radical Party President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2301144394 Paris AFP in English 1438 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2301144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 23 (AFP) -- Andre Rossinot, France's 
minister of civil service and the mayor of Nancy, was elected 
president of the centre-right Radical Party Sunday [23 January], 
a post he already headed in the 1980s. 
  A veteran French politician who was close to the 
conservative 
former prime minister Raymond Barre, Rossinot has been a deputy 
for the center-right Union for French Democracy (UDF), of which 
the Radicals are a component, in the Meurthe-et-Moselle region 
since 1978. 
  He was a member of the Radical Party's Executive Committee 
in 
1978 and its secretary general in 1979. He became president of 
the party between 1983-88. 
  He has been mayor of the northeastern city of Nancy since 
1983. 

