<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Neocommunist Congress Elects New Leader </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301200494 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1845 
GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2301200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The congress of the neocommunists is drawing to a 
close. The congress has elected a new party secretary in Fausto 
Bertinotti. There were bitter arguments over the decision to 
change the Communist Refoundation Party into a force for 
government. Guido Dell'Acquila reports: 
  [Dell'Acquila] The change in the Refoundation Party has been 
achieved. The manifesto proposed by the United Left group, 
which faced the thorny issue of governing the country, obtained 
70 percent of the delegates' votes. In other words the 
majority, led by Cossutta, Magri, and Bertinotti, saw their 
manifesto win approval by a wide margin. However, the margin 
does not conceal the deep splits and the anxiety which this 
choice provoked. 
  The results of the vote to elect a new executive will not be 
known for a few more hours. It is already known, however, that 
Bertinotti will be the new party secretary. He replaces 
Garavini, who resigned six months ago. In the meantime Cossutta 
has been reelected to the post of party chairman. After four 
days of debate this congress for change is coming to an end. 
The Refoundation Party, which is more used to being in 
opposition, is looking at the new political set-up with a 
mixture of hope and regret. 

</TEXT>

