<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundeswehr Soldiers To Withdraw from Somalia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401181194 Hamburg DPA in German 1724 GMT 24 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2401181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The return to Germany of the 1,300 
Bundeswehr servicemen still in Somalia is to be accomplished by 
a combined air-sea operation for security reasons, German 
Defense Minister Volker Ruehe decided today, a ministry 
spokesman announced. The operation is to start at the beginning 
of February and -- just like the return of the Americans -- be 
completed at the end of March. 
  The Defense Ministry's plans currently envisage first of 
all, 
transporting German servicemen from the Somali capital of 
Mogadishu by German naval vessels, probably to Mombasa (Kenya). 
The return flight to Germany will then be from there. 
  According to the ministry, Ruehe intends to avoid the 
possible risks of transporting them by air in the Mogadishu 
area, and thus to aim for a higher degree of security for the 
servicemen. The plans were closely connected with the U.S. 
Government decision to transport its personnel initially by sea. 

</TEXT>

