<H3> <TI>   Poland's Milewski Wants `Shield' Against Threats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401191794 Hamburg DPA in German 1711 GMT 24 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2401191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Berlin (DPA) -- In view of Defense Minister 
Volker Ruehe, the European continent still lacks the stability 
needed for it to grow closer together. Nevertheless, the NATO 
summit two weeks ago has set decisive signals with its 
Partnership for Peace initiative, Ruehe said at a security 
policy conference in Berlin on Monday [24 January]. [passage 
omitted] 
  Polish Deputy Defense Minister Jerzy Milewski demanded a 
"political shield" for his country against external threats. 
The agreed Partnership for Peace was "good for tomorrow, but 
not good enough for today." The existing threat was less of a 
military than of a political nature, and had arisen after the 
fall of the Berlin Wall and the disappearance of the old Soviet 
Union. Hence, Poland was also seeking less military than 
political support. Integrating his country into NATO would, in 
Milewski's view, not in any way be directed against Russia. 
With reference to Moscow's fears of encirclement, he said it 
was impossible to see how Moscow's security depended on Poland 
or Estonia. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

