<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, Bundesbank `in Full Agreement' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101142394 Hamburg DPA in German 1317 GMT 21 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2101142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Bonn (DPA) -- According to government spokesman 
Dieter Vogel, the government and the German Bundesbank are "in 
full agreement" in their assessment of the economic situation. 
After the severe recession in 1993, Bonn is expecting economic 
growth of 0.5 to 1 percent this year in western Germany and 6 to 
8 percent in eastern Germany, but there is still an unemployment 
figure for western Germany, which will be up to 450,000 higher. 
  Bundesbank President Hans Tietmeyer has said at the session 
of the economic cabinet of the federal government in Bonn on 
Friday [21 January] that the Bundesbank fully agreed with the 
outlines of the government's annual economic report, Vogel told 
the media. Tietmeyer said this applied, in particular, to 
avoiding forced interest rate reductions and to a policy of 
devaluation. 
  Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who chaired the session, stressed, 
according to Vogel, "the firm intention of the government to 
adhere to the cooperation between the government and the 
Bundesbank, as in the past." 
  Vogel said Economic Affairs Minister Guenther Rexrodt told 
the economic cabinet, which includes 10 of the 19 government 
ministers, that the starting point for economic development this 
year was "relatively favorable." This applied to both eastern 
and western Germany. In eastern Germany, however, there was 
still no self-sustaining upturn in sight. [passage omitted] 
  The government's main justification for its relatively 
optimistic assessment of the economy in the draft annual 
economic report is "better prospects for exports." The economic 
situation was improving in most parts of the world and slowly in 
Europe too. The economic revival was increasing investment 
activity. This fitted in with the type of goods German industry 
offers. For this reason, Bonn is expecting a rise in exports of 
3 to 4 percent in real terms in 1994, following a fall of 11.1 
percent last year. [passage omitted] 
  The government is expecting, at best, a small increase in 
investment in the company sector in western Germany and a rise 
of 12 to 14 percent in eastern Germany. This means a rise of 3 
to 4 percent in real terms for all of Germany. On the other 
hand, public investment would fall markedly because of the 
difficult budgetary situation. There was no indication of a 
rise in infrastructural investment in eastern Germany either, 
where it had risen so much in the last three years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

