<H3> <TI>   Andreatta Urges Greater NATO Commitment to Mediterranean </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1901161094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1504 GMT 19 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1901161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "NATO: Andreatta on Greater </F>
Commitment to the Mediterranean"] 
  [Text] Rome, 19 Jan (ANSA) -- The possibility of a greater 
NATO commitment towards the Mediterranean, including forms of 
cooperation with countries in the region, was analyzed here 
today by Foreign Minister Beniamino Andreatta during a meeting 
with students of the Gorizia Institute for International and 
Diplomatic Sciences. 
  At the recent NATO summit, it was agreed that the Alliance 
presence in Europe should be bolstered and, in this context, the 
partners discussed the possibility that the Western European 
Union [WEU] might conduct military operations, using NATO 
logistical support, he continued. This could provide an element 
of flexibility whereby the Europeans could resort to the use of 
force in a particular situation, without automatically involving 
the United States, he explained. 
  The minister went on to discuss the possibility of 
projecting 
the Alliance farther into the Mediterranean both in terms of a 
formal extension of the partnership to other nations in the 
region, and in terms of cooperation between the WEU and friendly 
nations such as Egypt or Morocco, always within the NATO 
framework. 
  At present, this would be a dangerous hypothesis, but if the 
Mideast peace process goes forward it could be seen as a 
possible development, Andreatta said. 
  Moving on to matters of development cooperation, Andreatta 
said that the fundamental problem was the study of technologies 
more suitable to nations of the south and to their transfer. 

</TEXT>

