<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Andreatta `Not Very Optimistic' on Bosnia Peace Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2001110194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2129 GMT 19 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2001110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Italy's Andreatta Not Optimistic on </F>
New Peace Plan"] 
  [Text] Rome, 19 Jan (ANSA) -- Italian Foreign Minister 
Beniamino Andreatta is not very optimistic on the possibility 
that opposing forces in Bosnia will accept the latest peace 
proposals put forward by the European Union. "The reactions of 
Muslims, Croats and Serbs have left little room for optimism" 
Italy's diplomatic chief said here during a debate on the 
ex-Yugoslavia, adding how they seem more "prone to military 
confrontations" than accepting the European plan for 
three-republic confederation. 
  The Muslims, he added, appear to have now also adopted the 
negotiations as a tool to buy time to re-conquer lost territory, 
and gaining influence among them were "external" forces and 
local "fundamentalist tendencies." 
  Also taking part in the debate, organized by the Rome 
vicariate, was Cardinal Roger Etchegaray who underscored how a 
peace based on land swapping could not be a long lasting one. 
  In Geneva, the self-proclaimed Serb and Croat republics in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina announced how they had hammered out an 
agreement to "sign a long-lasting peace" and establish "official 
relations...in the interest of promoting economic and political 
ties" adding how "no bilateral problems exist which cannot be 
resolved through peace means." 
  The official negotiations in Geneva on Bosnia, mediated by 
the European Union and the United Nations, were postponed today 
until February 10, with the European Union's chief mediator, 
David Owen, underscoring how "the situation is very dangerous 
and serious" and that negotiation must continue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

